Terminology

Number of Variables Involved

  • Univariate data analysis - distribution of single variable
  • Bivariate data analysis - relationship between two variables
  • Multivariate data analysis - relationship between many variables at once, usually focusing on the relationship between two while conditioning for others

Types of Variables

  • Numerical variables can be classified as continuous or discrete based on whether or not the variable can take on an infinite number of values or only non-negative whole numbers, respectively.
  • If the variable is categorical, we can determine if it is ordinal based on whether or not the levels have a natural ordering.

Visualizing Numerical Data

Describing the distribution of a variable

For any single numerical variable a researcher should report on the center, shape, and spread (variability) of the variable distribution. The researcher should also mention any unusual features in the distribution.

  • shape:
    • skewness: right-skewed, left-skewed, symmetric (skew is to the side of the longer tail)
    • modality: unimodal, bimodal, multimodal, uniform
  • center: mean (mean), median (median), mode (not always useful)
  • spread: range (range), standard deviation (sd), inter-quartile range (IQR)
  • unusual observations (gaps, outliers, etc.)

For now we are going to focus on shape. We will focus on the other parts in the next section.

Some typical shapes of data distributions are

Source: https://math.oxford.emory.edu/site/math117/shapeCenterAndSpread/



Histograms

Lets first look at the numerical variable loan_amount. The code below generates a histogram of loan_amount.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Notice we get a warning about the number of bins.

Changing the bin size of a histogram

For histograms it may depend on the binwidth as to how well you can determine the shape of the data. When you are looking at shape you want to determine an overall general trend.

Binwidth = 1000

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1000)

Setting a binwidth of 1000 in the context of loan_amount means that each vertical bar has a width of $1000. The above histogram is too detailed to determine an overall general trend.

Binwidth = 5000

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000)

The above histogram can help determine more of a general trend.

Binwidth = 20000

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 20000)

The above graph with 20000 bins is not detailed enough to see trends in the data.

Based on the histogram with binwidth = 5000, the distribution of loan_amount is unimodal and right skewed.


Customizing Histogram with labels

Graphs and plots should provide appropriate titles and axis labels.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000) +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  )

Change Color of histogram

You can change the color of a histogram graph by adding arguments to the aestheticsgeom_histogram()` function.

For a histogram, if we use the argument color this will add a color on the border of the bars. Notice the name of the color is in quotations.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000, color="orange") +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  )

For a histogram, if we use the argument fill this will fill the bars with a color.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000, color="orange", fill="purple") +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  )


Fill histogram with categorical variable

It is possible to break down numerical graphs by a categorical variable in order to compare groups.

Adding the fill aesthetic shows the different categories. Adding alpha=0.5 within the geom_histogram function gives the shaded areas of the categories a little bit (50%) of transparency.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, 
                  fill = homeownership)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000, alpha=0.5) +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  )

Facet with a categorical variable

Using the facet function

  • will provide Smaller plots that display different subsets of the data
  • is useful for exploring conditional relationships and large data

Below is the code for creating a histogram of the variable loan_amount with a separate graph for each type of homeownership. The nrow argument gives the number of rows wanted in the output.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, fill = homeownership)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000) +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ homeownership, nrow = 3)

Note: You can also facet based on two categorical variables by using code such as

facet_wrap(A~B) versus facet_wrap(~B)

In addition to the facet_wrap function you can use the facet_grid function.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, fill = homeownership)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000) +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  ) +
  facet_grid(~ homeownership)

Density Plot

Density plots use a kernel density estimate to show the probability density function of the variable. It is a smoothed version of the histogram and is used in the same concept.2

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_density()

Desity plots and adjusting banwidth

The banwidth of a density plot will determine how smooth the density curve is. Just like with histograms, the bandwidth can be adjusted to help determine an overal trend of the data.

adjust = 0.5

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_density(adjust = 0.5)

adjust = 1

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_density(adjust = 1)

adjust = 2

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_density(adjust = 2)


Customizing Density Plots

Adding title and axis labels.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_density(adjust = 2) +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Density",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  )

Changing color

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_density(adjust = 2, color="orange") +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Density",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  )

Adding a Categorical Variable

Just like with histograms, we can provide more detail about a density plot by separating by a categorical variable using the fill argument. As with histograms the alpha argument gives the shaded areas of the categories a little bit of transparency.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, 
                  fill = homeownership)) +
  geom_density(adjust = 2, 
               alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Density",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans", 
    fill = "Homeownership"
  )

Boxplots

A boxplot gives a nice summary of one or several numeric variables. The line that divides the box into 2 parts represents the median of the data. The end of the box shows the upper and lower quartiles. The extreme lines show the highest and lowest value excluding outliers.2

A boxplot is a graph that gives you a good indication of how the values in the data are spread out. Although boxplots may seem primitive in comparison to a histogram or density plot, they have the advantage of taking up less space, which is useful when comparing distributions between many groups or datasets. 3

Creating Boxplots

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Customizing Boxplots

Adding Labels and titles

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  ) +
  theme(
    axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
    axis.text.y = element_blank()
  )

The theme function in the above code is eliminating the tick marks and text from the y-axis for the boxplot. This is done because for this variable those values do not add value to the interpretation of the boxplot.
#### Adding Color

Just like a histogram, to change the color of the boxplot we can use the arguments color and fill within the geom_boxplot function.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_boxplot(color="orange", fill="purple") +
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  ) +
  theme(
    axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
    axis.text.y = element_blank()
  )

Adding a Categorical Variable

We can now add a grouping variable to the boxplot similar to what we did for histograms. The grouping variable will be added using the y argument in the aes() function in ggplot.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount,
                  y = homeownership)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans", 
    subtitle = "by type of homeownership"
  )

If we want to color the boxplot with a different color for each type of homeownership, we use the fill argument in the aes() function in ggplot.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount,
                  y = homeownership, fill=homeownership)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans", 
    subtitle = "by type of homeownership"
  )

Scatterplot

We have seen previously seen how to look at the relationship between 2 numerical variables using a scatterplot.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_point()

Custimizing Scatterplots

Adding Labels

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_point()  + 
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
    y = "Annual Income ($)", 
    title = "Scatterplot Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  )

Changing Point Color

You can change the color of the points in a scatterplot by adding color argument to the geom_point() function.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_point(color="orange") +
   labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
    y = "Annual Income ($)", 
    title = "Scatterplot Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  )

Changing Point Size

You can change the point size with the argument size in the geom_point() function.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_point(color="orange", size=4) + 
   labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
    y = "Annual Income ($)", 
    title = "Scatterplot Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  )

Changing Point Type

You can change the type or shape of the points by designatinge shape corresponding to the following table.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_point(color="orange", 
             size=2, 
             shape = 17) + 
   labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
    y = "Annual Income ($)", 
    title = "Scatterplot Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  )

Adding in Categorical Variable

We have already seen how you can add coloring for a categorical variable by adding color equal to a categorical variable to the aesthetics.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income, color=homeownership)) +
  geom_point(size=2, 
             shape = 17) + 
   labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
    y = "Annual Income ($)", 
    title = "Scatterplot Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  )

You can also change the size of the point for each value of a categorical variable

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income, size=homeownership)) +
  geom_point(color="orange", 
             shape = 17) + 
   labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
    y = "Annual Income ($)", 
    title = "Scatterplot Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  ) 
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

Or the type

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income, shape = homeownership)) +
  geom_point(color="orange", 
             size = 3) + 
   labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
    y = "Annual Income ($)", 
    title = "Scatterplot Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  )

Hexplot

Another way to look at this relationship is with hexplots. Hexplots are 2D plots in which bins are diplayed in hexagons and the color represents the number of data points within each bin.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_hex()

Note:

You may need to install the package hexbin R Studio for the hexplot to work. You will also need to load the hexbin in you R Markdown file (there is a spot to do this at the top of the template that says Load packages needed but you can put it anywhere.)


Customizing Hexplot

You can change the discrete color of the hexplot by using color and fill.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_hex(color="orange", fill="purple") + 
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = "Annual Income ($)",
    title = "Hexplot of Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  )

However, if you want to keep the gradient nature but change the color pallete you can use some of the scale_fill_XXX functions. Below we have used scale_fill_viridis_c Changing the color of a hexplot while keeping the gradient

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_hex() + 
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = "Annual Income ($)",
    title = "Hexplot of Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  ) + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c()

Use Wrangling Tools to limit data

You may use the transformation or wrangling tools (filter, select, etc.) within (or outside of) ggplot to create a graph of a subset or the data.

Example using Hexplot

For example, you can create a hexplot for just annual_income values less than 500000. Typically the use of wrangling tools within the ggplot function are used in the first argument (where the dataset goes).

ggplot(loans %>% filter(annual_income < 500000), 
       aes(x = loan_amount, y = annual_income)) +
  geom_hex() + 
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = "Annual Income ($)",
    title = "Hexplot of Loan Amount versus Annual Income"
  ) + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c()

Violin Plot

A violin plot is a method of plotting numeric data. It is similar to a box plot, with the addition of a rotated kernel density plot on each side. 4

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership, y = loan_amount)) +
  geom_violin() + 
  labs(x = "Home Ownership", 
       y = "Loan Amount ($)", 
       title = "Violin Plot of Loan Amount by Home Ownership")

We can fill each plot with color for each type of homeownship using a method similar to what we did with boxplots.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership, y = loan_amount, fill=homeownership)) +
  geom_violin() + 
    labs(x = "Home Ownership", 
       y = "Loan Amount ($)", 
       title = "Violin Plot of Loan Amount by Home Ownership")


Ridge Plot

A Ridgeline plot (sometimes called Joyplot) shows the distribution of a numeric value for several groups. Distribution can be represented using histograms or density plots, all aligned to the same horizontal scale and presented with a slight overlap.2

library(ggridges)
ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount, 
                  y = grade, 
                  fill = grade, 
                  color = grade)) + 
  geom_density_ridges(alpha = 0.5) + 
    labs(x = "Loan Amount ($)", 
       y = "Grade", 
       title = "Ridge Plot Loan Amount by Grade")
## Picking joint bandwidth of 2360


Visualizing Categorical Data

Bar chart

A standard way to visually display one categorical (or factor) variable is with a bar chart. A basic bar chart of homeownership is given below.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership)) +
  geom_bar()


Customizing Bar Chart

Adding titles, colors, and labels to the bar chart.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership)) +
  geom_bar(color="orange", fill="purple") +
  labs(
    x="Homeownership", 
    y= "Count",
    title= "Frequency Chart of Homeownship"
  )

You can add frequency labels to the bar charts using geom_text(). I wont get into all the details of the function here but just so you know this is available.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership)) +
  geom_bar(color="orange", fill="purple") +
  geom_text(stat = "count", 
            aes(label = after_stat(count)), 
            vjust = 0) +
  labs(
    x="Homeownership", 
    y= "Count",
    title= "Frequency Chart of Homeownship"
  )

You can also change the orientation of the graph by making the variable of interest the y variable rather than the x variable.

ggplot(loans, aes(y = homeownership)) +
  geom_bar(color="orange", fill="purple") +
  labs(
    x="Count", 
    y= "Homeownership",
    title= "Frequency Chart of Homeownship"
  )

You can change the y axis to be proportion rather than frequency using the after_stat function in the aesthetics and the group=1 argument.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership, y=after_stat(prop), group=1)) +
  geom_bar(color="orange", fill="purple") +
  labs(
    x="Homeownership", 
    y= "Count",
    title= "Proportion Chart of Homeownship"
  )

Adding a Categorical Variable

You can add coloring for an additional categorical variable by using the fill argument. If you add the position = "dodge" code to the geom_bar() function this will give you a side-by-side bar graph.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership, fill=grade)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  labs(
    x="Homeownership", 
    y= "Count",
    title= "Frequency Chart of Homeownship"
  )

Segmented Bar Chart

A segmented bar chart provides a visual display of a categorical variable broken down by another categorical variable. There are two ways to represent a segmented bar chart. The difference has to do with what the height of the bars represents.

For the following bar chart the height of the vertical bars represents the count of each type of homeownership.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership, 
                  fill = grade)) +
  geom_bar() +
    labs(
    x="Homeownership", 
    y= "Count",
    title= "Frequency Chart of Homeownship"
  )

OR

For the next bar chart (adding `position=fill to the geom_bar function) the height of the vertical bars represents the percentage per each homeownership broken down by grade. Notice each bar represents 100% of each type of homeownership.

ggplot(loans, aes(x = homeownership, fill = grade)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill")

Think about which bar plot is a more useful representation for visualizing the relationship between homeownership and grade?

Highlighting specifics in graphs

There is a package called gghighlight that can help you hightlight a particular line, group, etc. in a graph. Below are some brief examples using this package. You can find out more here.

Histogram

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000, alpha=0.5, color="white", fill="blue") +
  labs(
    x = "Loan amount ($)",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans"
  ) +
  gghighlight::gghighlight(homeownership=="OWN")

Boxplot

ggplot(loans, aes(x = loan_amount,
                  y = homeownership, fill=homeownership)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Amounts of Lending Club loans", 
    subtitle = "by type of homeownership"
  ) +
  gghighlight::gghighlight(homeownership=="OWN")
